Designed by Major General George Schofield, the Smith and Wesson Model 1870 "Schofield" was a revolutionary design that broke open, ejecting all six spent cartridge cases automatically while providing easy access for re-loading. Fast re-loading being a distinct advantage in his line of work, Jessie James bought a pair as did John Wessley Hardin and Wild Bill Hickok.

Although the U.S. Army purchased 3,000 S&W Schofields with an improved top latch for cavalry troops, it was the Russian government that really embraced the new sidearm. With a slightly modified grip, lanyard ring and distinctive trigger-guard spur, the Czar ordered over 41,000 of the new S&W revolvers.

True to the originals, Uberti Top Breaks come in all three models including the Russian model with authentic Cyrillic barrel stampings.

title: For Sale:  802 firearms.
postcontent:
I just wanna take a second to show some respect. I have been looking for a solid carry for awhile and keeping an eye on this board, after sending some emails I wound up corresponding with George (I believe) from 802 firearms. I knew nothing about them and seemed pretty set in what I wanted. I met him however at his shop and he had all of the pieces layed out that fit my criteria and budget. 

He was polite and professional and knew a lot about guns, and his prices were unmatched. He didn't pressure me to buy and was happy to just talk about guns. What made the experience great was his inventory. He has some obscure guns for VERY affordable prices. I had never seen the EAA distributed "witness", and in this pictures it looked okay, but in person it's another story. I decided I needed one eventually and added that and a ride he has stocked to "to buy" list. 

I seriously recommend anyone to give this place a shot, if there's something you need he will make it happen and for a price you can feel good about. If you have a large or small budget, from hi point to a kimber 1911 he's got you, and he is right in downtown Burlington (However just a heads up that it's by appointment only!!). I was hesitant to check it out as well, but if you're shopping for a new firearm, do yourself a favor and go there first, even if you don't get something you'll discover there's something you didn't know before that you "needed". 

I have no affiliation, I just appreciate hard work and good customer service. We need more shops like this.

title: For Sale:  Stoeger Cougar / Beretta Cougar 8040-F
postcontent:
Stoeger Cougar 40 S&W
2x magazines
Factory paperwork
Factory box
Factory Lock
Factory test round spent brass with signed inspection

This is the exact same as the Beretta Cougar. When Beretta started making the polymer PX4, they moved their tooling to their Stoeger factory so they could keep producing the Cougar. Beretta, Stoeger, Benelli, Franchi, & Uberti are all the same company.

Now that that's out of the way...this is basically brand new. It's been to the range one time. I'm only selling it to fund other stuff.

This is bar-none...the softest shooting 40 S&W I've ever shot. The mechanics behind the Cougar design make it absorb the recoil quite well. The barrel rotates 30 degrees when the slide cycles, then rotates back and locks in place with locking lugs. (just like a M14 / Mini14) This is exceptionally nice for the 40 S&W because of the high pressure round's inherent muzzle-flip. With less recoil and less muzzle flip, your follow-up shots are much quicker than a standard blow-back design.

The single action / double action trigger is so much better than today's striker-fired pistols. It has the De-cocker / safety and even a half-cocked feature if you want to carry it with the safety off, but not go through the entire DA travel. (genius) The safety can easily be converted to a decocker only via some quick video online.

I was skeptical at first, but recoil is noticeably less...and more accurate than other 40 S&W's I've shot.

I just noticed that the slide has a spot that the finish is thin. (If that bugs you)

I'm not in a hurry to see this one go, but if you can meet my price, then I'll get moving on my other project, I guess.

email, text, whateve

title: For Sale:  Taurus 1911 1911AR aluminum with rail and accessories
location: Concord, 10 minutes north of Charlotte, Charlotte, North Carolina
postcontent:
This was purchased new for myself to see if I could get accustomed to the 1911 platform.  I just never shoot it anymore.  Was used only for range practice and never carried.

I have replaced a few items on the pistol, but anyone familiar with 1911's can easily switch them back to the OEM parts.

1)  The Taurus hammer was replaced with a Nighthawk skeletonized hammer.  The OEM hammer has the keyed safety built into the hammer and I found that it occassionally wanted to rotate to the lock position while shooting which would disable the firearm.  The OEM hammer and Taurus keys are both included.

2)  The OEM straight-eight sights were replaced with a Novak rear adjustable to make this a 3-dot sight.  I tried the straight-eight setup, but it just was NOT for me and my groups were not tight.  The replacement Novak sight is cut to Taurus's proprietory slide cute and are a direct replacement.  Meaning, the OEM sights will slide right back in if you desire the straight-eight setup.

3)  A Smith-and-Alexander flared mag well was added.  This pistol just seemed to need one so I added it.  It swaps easily with a single pin removal and the OEM mainspring housing is included if you want it removed.

4)  I added a pair of G10 grips that are black/grey in color along with new black allen head screws.  The OEM grips are included.  Grips are just a personal preference and the allen head screws just dress it up.

5) A paddle holster designed specifically for the railed Taurus 1911 is included.  Mint condition as I never wore it except for while at the range.

Besides the not trusting the OEM hammer on this pistol and replacing, the only thing that I had a problem with was the ambidextrous thumb safety.  A common problem with ambi safeties is that the right side can become loose.  I believe that the OEM Taurus ambi safety is a metal injected part and simply not as strong as a milled part.  Because the OEM safety became loose, I attempted to tighted the ears with a little pressure and it broke.  A phone call to Taurus indicated that they would NOT sell directly me anything related to the safety system on the firearm and would only replace if I shipped them the pistol.  Therefore I searched for a replacement ambi safety that is shaped the same as OEM.  The model used is a Cylinder-and-Slide ambi safety which is a milled part instead of metal-injected.  I was mainly selected because it matched the OEM safety in regards to shape and design.

Both OEM magazines come with the pistol.  Included is the OEM carry case with an un-used cleaning rode.  Both security keys for the Taurus OEM hammer are included.  I have the original warrenty card as well as the instruction manual.

I would rate this pistol in excellent condition (ie. that's one step down from mint in my opinion) simply because I have shot this pistol.  Normal wear points on the slide and barrel are all that is different from this pistol being brand new.  There are no signs of abuse or damage, nor any scratches due to disassembly.  I would estimate this firearm to be a low-round-count with less than 500 rounds.

Overall, it's a great gun but I just don't believe that I'm a 1911 person.  The price is FIRM.

All laws will be followed for this sale.  I will need to see a CWP or a pistol permit with matching identification from North Carolina.  A receipt will be written and provided to both parties.  A location will be agreed to meet that is near Concord.  Cash only will be accepted.

title: For Sale:  WWII pistol - Manuhrin P1 9mm w/ original holster and extra magazine - Walther P38 variation
postcontent:
Very nice example of the Manuhrin P1 in 9mm with holster and extra magazine.  Email, call, or text me at 615-4five;six- 458five.

A variation of the the P38, the P1 was one of the world's first true double-action pistol and proved to be an exceptional military pistol. The weapon is robust, accurate and well balanced and field stripping and maintenance are simple and rapid. The P1 uses a double-action trigger design similar to that of the earlier Walther PPKs, and a loaded chamber indicator is also incorporated. The fixed-barrel design mechanism operates by use of a wedge-shaped locking block underneath the breech. The standard safety also acts as a decocker, and is located at the left side of the slide. When German manufacturer Walther was no longer able to produce firearms after World War II thanks to Allied sanctions, they passed the design and materials for the P38 and P1 over to French firearms company Manurhin. This pistol is import-marked and features synthetic grips, fixed open sights, and an 8-round magazine. Its grips, metal, and bore are all in very good condition.

Email, call, or text me at 615-4five;six- 458five.
